LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lindsay  .","Irish: shortened and Anglicized form of various Gaelic surnames, as for example <b>Ó Loingsigh</b> (see   Lynch   1), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntóg</b> (see   McClintock  ), and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn   and   Lynn  )."],"variants":[{"name":"McClintock","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gille Fhionndaig</b> ‘son of the servant of (Saint) <i>Fionntóg</i>’, a personal name derived from a pet form of <i>fionn</i> ‘white’. Compare   Lindsey  .","History: A Scottish family of this name settled in Donegal in the late 16th century."]},{"name":"Lindsay","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Lindsey in Lincolnshire, England. This is first found in the form <i>Lindissi</i>, apparently a derivative of the British name of   Lincoln  . To this was later added the Old English element <i>ēg</i> ‘island’, since the place was virtually cut off by the surrounding fenland. The surname was taken to Scotland at an early date and is the name of an important and powerful Scottish family.","Irish: adopted as an equivalent ofvarious Gaelic names (see   Lindsey  )."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Lindsey was born about 1094, in Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Baldric De Lindsay, was 31 and her mother, Bilelde Saint-Sauveur, was 25. She had at least 2 sons and 3 daughters with Simon Fitzwilliam de Kyme. She died in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1094–":"umbes 1094–Surnud","1083–Male":"1083–Surnud","1094–Female":"1094–Surnud","1094–1162":"1094–1162","1094–Male":"1094–Surnud","1124–1194":"1124–1194","1129–Female":"1129–Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1143–1214":"1143–1214","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","1064–1096":"1064–1096","1070–1094":"1070–1094","1143":"1143","1064":"1064","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","1094":"1094","1083":"1083","1070":"1070","1129":"1129","1214":"1214","1124":"1124","1145":"1145","Abt 1143":"umbes 1143","about 1145":"umbes 1145","Abt 1094":"umbes 1094","about 1130":"umbes 1130","Kyme, Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England":"Kyme, Lincolnshire, England","Sotby, Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England":"Sotby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Horncastle, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1094–":"noin 1094–Kuollut","1083–Male":"1083–Kuollut","1094–Female":"1094–Kuollut","1094–1162":"1094–1162","1094–Male":"1094–Kuollut","1124–1194":"1124–1194","1129–Female":"1129–Kuollut","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1143–1214":"1143–1214","1145–Female":"1145–Kuollut","1064–1096":"1064–1096","1070–1094":"1070–1094","1143":"1143","1064":"1064","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1162":"1162","1194":"1194","1094":"1094","1083":"1083","1070":"1070","1129":"1129","1214":"1214","1124":"1124","1145":"1145","Abt 1143":"noin 1143","about 1145":"noin 1145","Abt 1094":"noin 1094","about 1130":"noin 1130","Kyme, Sleaford, Lincolnsh